{
  "global": "Interpret CRISPR-HaloTag Western blot data across four species-variable clonal cell lines and an endogenous-tagging localization experiment to characterize protein isoforms, species identity, experimental completeness, and true in-vivo receptor localization.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Analyze anti-HaloTag Western blot band patterns to determine properties of the tagged protein (Part 1A)",
      "atomics": [
        "Note that the anti-HaloTag antibody detects only HaloTag-fused protein, so every visible band contains HaloTag (~33 kDa)",
        "Observe that lanes 1, 3, and 4 each show two bands while lane 2 shows one band",
        "Calculate intra-lane band mass differences: Lane 1 = 106-73 = 33 kDa, Lane 3 = 108-75 = 33 kDa, Lane 4 = 113-80 = 33 kDa, all matching HaloTag mass",
        "Conclude the protein has at least two isoforms (likely arising from alternative splicing) and that both isoforms are tagged by the CRISPR knock-in at that locus"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Explain why observed kDa values vary across the four cell lines (Part 1B)",
      "atomics": [
        "Attribute primary variation to species-level sequence divergence: orthologous proteins in different species have different amino acid compositions and thus different molecular weights",
        "Attribute dual-band vs single-band differences to species-specific alternative splicing patterns generating isoforms of different sizes",
        "Note that differential post-translational modifications (glycosylation, phosphorylation) across species further shift apparent MW on SDS-PAGE"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Identify which cell lines are likely from the same species (Part 1C)",
      "atomics": [
        "Align all band positions: L1={73,106}, L2={108}, L3={75,108}, L4={80,113}",
        "Identify the shared 108 kDa band in both Lane 2 and Lane 3 as evidence of an identical ortholog size",
        "Explain the L2 single-band vs L3 double-band discrepancy as cell-type-specific isoform expression or CRISPR insertion disrupting a splice site in the L2 clone",
        "Conclude Lane 2 and Lane 3 are likely from the same species; Lane 1 and Lane 4 are each from distinct species"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Identify the one critical experimental design detail and one critical protein detail required to determine experimental success (Part 1D)",
      "atomics": [
        "Experimental design detail: confirmation that HaloTag was inserted at the correct genomic locus via HDR (verified by junction PCR or Sanger sequencing), ruling out random plasmid integration",
        "Protein detail: the expected molecular weight of the protein of interest, so that observed band sizes can be verified as (native protein MW + 33 kDa HaloTag)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Interpret what cytoplasmic puncta localization from endogenous HaloTag says about the receptor compared to overexpression data (Part 2A)",
      "atomics": [
        "Recognize the localization discrepancy as an overexpression artifact: excess protein from virus transfection saturates normal trafficking machinery, routing it to a non-native compartment",
        "Conclude the true physiological localization is cytoplasmic puncta (consistent with endosomes, vesicles, or related compartments)",
        "State the biological implication: the receptor's function and signaling context should be studied at the endogenous puncta location, not the previously reported overexpression-driven site"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Propose one validation step for the HaloTag endogenous tagging result (Part 2B)",
      "atomics": [
        "Perform immunofluorescence using a validated antibody against the endogenous receptor (epitope outside HaloTag) to confirm identical cytoplasmic puncta localization independent of the tag",
        "Alternatively, co-stain HaloTag signal with a known organelle marker (e.g., EEA1 for early endosomes, Rab7 for late endosomes) to assign puncta to a specific compartment and confirm biological plausibility"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Cross-validate the 33 kDa intra-lane doublet hypothesis: confirm the mass difference is consistent with HaloTag and not with proteolytic cleavage artifacts or non-specific bands by checking whether the lower band disappears upon protease inhibitor treatment or longer exposure",
    "Connect the endogenous-tagging principle from Part 2 back to Part 1: the CRISPR knock-in strategy used in Part 1 is the same gold-standard endogenous approach described in Part 2, reinforcing why single-cell clone verification and locus sequencing (Part 1D) are essential"
  ],
  "gold_actions": {
    "global": "Subtract 33 kDa (HaloTag mass) from each Western blot band to recover native protein isoform sizes, use shared band positions to assign species identity, enumerate two missing experimental parameters needed to validate the experiment, then apply overexpression-artifact logic to interpret cytoplasmic puncta as the true receptor localization and propose an antibody-based co-stain as validation.",
    "subtasks": [
      {
        "subtask": "Subtract HaloTag mass from each band to recover native isoform sizes and establish that the protein produces at least two isoforms both captured by the CRISPR knock-in",
        "atomics": [
          "Apply anti-HaloTag detection rule: every visible band = HaloTag-fused protein; naked protein is invisible to this antibody",
          "Compute native sizes: L1 = 73-33=40 kDa and 106-33=73 kDa; L2 = 108-33=75 kDa; L3 = 75-33=42 kDa and 108-33=75 kDa; L4 = 80-33=47 kDa and 113-33=80 kDa",
          "Verify that intra-lane differences (33 kDa in L1, L3, L4) exactly match HaloTag MW, confirming both bands per lane are distinct isoforms of the same tagged gene rather than non-specific signal",
          "Conclude the gene produces ≥2 isoforms (most likely via alternative splicing) and both isoforms are successfully tagged by the CRISPR knock-in at the shared locus"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Attribute kDa variation between lanes to species-level ortholog sequence divergence and differential isoform expression, with PTMs as a secondary contributor",
        "atomics": [
          "Map differing band positions (73/106 vs 75/108 vs 80/113) to amino-acid-sequence differences between species orthologs, which change polypeptide MW",
          "Attribute presence of two bands in L1/L3/L4 but only one in L2 to species-specific alternative splicing: L2 species may only express the larger isoform in this cell type",
          "Note glycosylation and phosphorylation state differences between species as tertiary contributors to apparent MW shifts on denaturing SDS-PAGE"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Identify Lane 2 and Lane 3 as likely from the same species based on the shared 108 kDa band representing an identical ortholog MW",
        "atomics": [
          "Tabulate unique band positions: only L2 and L3 share an identical band at exactly 108 kDa",
          "Interpret shared 108 kDa as evidence both lines harbor the same ortholog sequence (same species), producing a protein of ~75 kDa native MW + 33 kDa HaloTag",
          "Explain L2 single-band: this clone or cell type does not express the smaller isoform (~42 kDa native), possibly due to tissue-specific splicing or CRISPR insertion disrupting an upstream splice acceptor",
          "Declare L1 (bands at 73/106) and L4 (bands at 80/113) each from distinct species, different from each other and from the L2/L3 species"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "State junction-PCR/sequencing as the missing experiment-design detail and expected protein MW as the missing protein detail, both required to declare the tagging experiment a success",
        "atomics": [
          "Experiment design detail: junction PCR or Sanger sequencing spanning the HaloTag insertion site must confirm HDR-mediated integration at the correct endogenous locus, ruling out random plasmid integration that would also yield an anti-HaloTag-positive band",
          "Protein detail: the annotated or computationally predicted molecular weight of the untagged protein must be known so that observed band MW minus 33 kDa can be compared to the expected native size, confirming the correct protein is being detected"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Apply overexpression-artifact logic to conclude cytoplasmic puncta is the true physiological localization and the prior virus-transfection result was an artifact",
        "atomics": [
          "Reason mechanistically: virus-based overexpression floods the secretory/trafficking pathway, causing the receptor to accumulate at a non-native membrane compartment that mimics functional localization",
          "Conclude that at endogenous expression levels the receptor traffics to and resides in cytoplasmic puncta, likely intracellular vesicles or endosomal compartments",
          "State the practical consequence: receptor signaling studies using overexpression data may have attributed function to the wrong subcellular location; endogenous HaloTag data should supersede those findings",
          "Note that 'competent form' seen in overexpression reflects a protein that can fold and traffic but is driven to an artifactual location by abundance"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Propose immunofluorescence with an anti-protein antibody (epitope outside HaloTag) as the single validation step to confirm HaloTag accurately reports endogenous localization",
        "atomics": [
          "Stain cells expressing endogenous HaloTag-receptor with a rabbit polyclonal or monoclonal antibody targeting an epitope in the native receptor sequence (not the HaloTag), then image both channels and compute Pearson co-localization coefficient",
          "Expected result: HaloTag fluorescence and anti-receptor antibody signal co-localize in cytoplasmic puncta at >0.8 Pearson coefficient, confirming the HaloTag does not alter localization and both signals report the same compartment"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "global_atomics": [
      "Run a negative control lane (untagged parental cell lysate) alongside all four lanes to confirm no anti-HaloTag cross-reactivity, validating that every detected band is genuinely HaloTag-fused and that the 33 kDa doublet logic holds",
      "Synthesize Parts 1 and 2: both use endogenous CRISPR-HaloTag knock-in strategy; Part 1D locus-verification requirement directly parallels Part 2's validation rationale—endogenous tagging is only trustworthy when correct integration is sequence-confirmed and the native protein size matches expectations"
    ]
  }
}
```
